Four datasets are selected according to the given requirements.

In the first dataset there are more than 50 variables (fetures) It has 54 features.This is a regression problem. The data is not all numerical. There are categorical and ordinal variables. The data is about Facebook Comment Volume. Number of training samples are much more than 200. It is trying to estimate the data o 54th feature in the dataset.

#data  1 is prepared
TrainData <- read.csv(file="C:/Users/Gizem/Desktop/hw4gz/Features_Variant_1.csv", header=FALSE, sep=",")
TestData = read.csv(file="C:/Users/Gizem/Desktop/dataminig1/Dataset/Testing/TestSet/Test_Case_1.csv", header=FALSE, sep=",")

Decision Tree for 1st Dataset

# Decision Tree
require(rpart.plot)
for (i in 1:3){
  set.seed(124)
  desiciontree1 <- rpart(V54 ~ V1 + V2 + V3 + V4 + V5 + V6 + V7 + V8 + V9 + V10 + V11 + V12 + V13+ V14 + V15 + V16 + V17 + V18 + V19 + V20 + V21 + V22 + V23+ V24 + V25 +
                           V26 + V27 + V28 + V29 + V30 + V31 + V32 + V33+ V34 + V35 + V36 + V37 + V38 + V39 + V40 + V41 + V42 + V43+ V44 + V45 + V46 + V47 + V48 + V49 + V50 
                         + V51 + V52 + V53, data=TrainData, control=rpart.control(minbucket = 2+i,cp=0.005*i),method = "anova")
  
  rpart.plot(desiciontree1,type = 3,digits = 3,fallen.leaves = TRUE)
  #Predictions
  pred1train<-predict(desiciontree1,TrainData)
  #Mean Absolute Error for train data
  
  MeanAbsError<-function(actual,predicted){mean(abs(actual - predicted))
  }
  pred1test<-predict(desiciontree1,TestData)
  
  #mean absolute error for train data is found as
  print(MeanAbsError(TrainData$V54,pred1train))
  #mean absolute error for test data is found as
  print(MeanAbsError(TestData$V54,pred1test))
}

# Support Vector Machines

library(e1071)

#the original train data had 40949 observations with 54 variables which required a very long run time in r for support vector machine code
#Therefore a short version of train data is used for this svm method for time concerns. This short version contains 200 observations with 54 variables.

ShortofTrainData <- read.csv(file="C:/Users/Gizem/Desktop/hw4gz/shortof_Features_Variant_1.csv", header=FALSE, sep=",")

2nd Dataset

In the second data set, there are more than 50 features. The dataset is about diabetes. This is a classification problem. The target integer can be selected from the dataset. It is metadata, there are nly features there is no specific target. The target is chosen as number of medications. The target of diabetesMED is also used for desicionteree for visual considerations.

Dataset is prepared. There was no test data, therefore it is created by using the coding below.

Datadiabet <- read.csv(file="C:/Users/Gizem/Desktop/dataset_diabetes/diabetic_data.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")
#Datadiabet <- read.csv(file="C:/Users/Gizem/Desktop/dataset_diabetes/na_deleted_diabetic_data.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")

## 75% of the sample size
smp_size <- floor(0.75 * nrow(Datadiabet))

## set the seed to make your partition reproducible
set.seed(123)
train_ind <- sample(seq_len(nrow(Datadiabet)), size = smp_size)

traindiabet <- Datadiabet[train_ind, ]
testdiabet <- Datadiabet[-train_ind, ]
# Decision Tree
require(rpart.plot)
for (i in 1:3){
  set.seed(124)
  desiciontree2 <- rpart(time_in_hospital~., data=traindiabet, control=rpart.control(minbucket = 2+i,cp=0.005*i),method = "anova")
  
  rpart.plot(desiciontree2,type = 3,digits = 3,fallen.leaves = TRUE)
  #Predictions
  pred2train<-predict(desiciontree2,traindiabet)
  #Mean Absolute Error for train data
  
  MeanAbsError<-function(actual,predicted){mean(abs(actual - predicted))
  }
  pred2test<-predict(desiciontree2,testdiabet)
  
  #mean absolute error for train data is found as
  print(MeanAbsError(traindiabet$time_in_hospital,pred2train))
  #mean absolute error for test data is found as
  print(MeanAbsError(testdiabet$time_in_hospital,pred2test))
}

Support Vector Machines for 2nd Datset

# Support Vector Machines 

library(e1071)
set.seed(124)
#the original train data had 25442 observations with 50 variables which required a very long run time in r for support vector machine code
#Therefore a short version of train data is used for this svm method for time concerns. This short version contains 200 observations with 54 variables.
#Also the variables that stayed constant during these 200 observations are eliminated for svm function to work. 
Shortoftraindiabet <- read.csv(file="C:/Users/Gizem/Desktop/hw4gz/shortof_diabetic_data.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")


shortfittedsvm<-svm(time_in_hospital~.,data = Shortoftraindiabet,kernel="radial")
print(shortfittedsvm)
## 
## Call:
## svm(formula = time_in_hospital ~ ., data = Shortoftraindiabet, 
##     kernel = "radial")
## 
## 
## Parameters:
##    SVM-Type:  eps-regression 
##  SVM-Kernel:  radial 
##        cost:  1 
##       gamma:  0.007407407 
##     epsilon:  0.1 
## 
## 
## Number of Support Vectors:  179
#with the same variables;
# 75% of the sample size
short_smp_size <- floor(0.75 * nrow(Shortoftraindiabet))

# set the seed to make your partition reproducible
set.seed(124)
train_ind <- sample(seq_len(nrow(Shortoftraindiabet)), size = short_smp_size)

short_traindiabet <- Shortoftraindiabet[train_ind, ]
short_testdiabet <- Shortoftraindiabet[-train_ind, ]
pred1svm<-predict(shortfittedsvm,short_testdiabet)
plot(pred1svm)

resultsvm<-cbind(short_testdiabet$time_in_hospital, data.frame(pred1svm))
error1svm=sum((resultsvm[,2] - mean(resultsvm[,2]))^2) / sum((resultsvm[,1] - mean(resultsvm[,1]))^2)
#"coefficient of determination is found as
print(error1svm)
## [1] 0.273013
pred1svmtest<-predict(shortfittedsvm,short_testdiabet)
plot(pred1svmtest)

result1svmtest<-cbind(short_testdiabet$time_in_hospital, data.frame(pred1svmtest))
error1scmtest=sum((result1svmtest[,2] - mean(result1svmtest[,2]))^2) / sum((result1svmtest[,1] - mean(result1svmtest[,1]))^2)
#coefficient of determination can be found as
print(error1scmtest)

3rd Dataset

In the third data set, there are more than 20 features. The dataset is about students academics performance. This is a multiclass problem. The target integer can be selected from the dataset. It is metadata, there are only features there is no specific target. The target is chosen as 21st column, the last feature.

Dataset 3 is prepared.There was no test data, therefore it is created by using the coding below.

#3
studentdata<- read.csv(file="C:/Users/Gizem/Desktop/hw4gz/data3b.csv", header=FALSE, sep=",")

## 75% of the sample size
smp_sizestud <- floor(0.75 * nrow(studentdata))

## set the seed to make your partition reproducible
set.seed(123)
train_indstud <- sample(seq_len(nrow(studentdata)), size = smp_sizestud)

trainstud <- studentdata[train_indstud, ]
teststud <- studentdata[-train_indstud, ]

Decision Tree for 3rd Data

# Decision Tree
require(rpart.plot)
for (i in 1:3){
  set.seed(124)
  desiciontree1 <- rpart(V21 ~ V1 + V2 + V3 + V4 + V5 + V6 + V7 + V8 + V9 + V10 + V11 + V12 + V13+ V14 + V15 + V16 + V17 + V18 + V19 + V20 , data=trainstud, control=rpart.control(minbucket = 2+i,cp=0.005*i),method = "anova")
  
  rpart.plot(desiciontree1,type = 3,digits = 3,fallen.leaves = TRUE)
  #Predictions
 pred1train<-predict(desiciontree1,trainstud)
  #Mean Absolute Error for train data
  
  MeanAbsError<-function(actual,predicted){mean(abs(actual - predicted))
  }
  pred1test<-predict(desiciontree1,teststud)
  
  #mean absolute error for train data is found as
  print(MeanAbsError(trainstud$V21,pred1train))
  #mean absolute error for test data is found as
  print(MeanAbsError(teststud$V21,pred1test))
}

4th Dataset

In the fourth data set, there are more than 20 features. The dataset is about frogs. The target integer can be selected from the dataset. It is metadata, there are only features there is no specific target. The target is chosen as Genus. Also recordID is chosen for stochastic gradient boosting method, since recordID had numerical data in the column which can be used for error calculations. Also class imbalance is done on this data by editing the raw data.

4th Dataset is prepared.There was no test data, therefore it is created by using the coding below.

Support Vector Machines with Genus

Class imbalance is done on this data by editing the raw data an turning the data into shortoftrainfrog fromtrainfrog. The Genus of Adenomera is chosen much more than the others.

library(e1071)
set.seed(124)
#the original train data had 1799 observations with 26 variables which required a very long run time in r for support vector machine code
#Therefore a short version of train data is used for this svm method for time concerns. This short version contains 218 observations
#from all over the data with 26 variables.

Shortoftrainfrog <- read.csv(file="C:/Users/Gizem/Desktop/hw4gz/Short_Frogs_MFCCs.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")


shortfittedsvm<-svm(Genus~.,data = Shortoftrainfrog,kernel="radial")
print(shortfittedsvm)
## 
## Call:
## svm(formula = Genus ~ ., data = Shortoftrainfrog, kernel = "radial")
## 
## 
## Parameters:
##    SVM-Type:  C-classification 
##  SVM-Kernel:  radial 
##        cost:  1 
##       gamma:  0.02857143 
## 
## Number of Support Vectors:  85
####with the same variables;
## 75% of the sample size
short_smp_size <- floor(0.75 * nrow(Shortoftrainfrog))

## set the seed to make your partition reproducible
set.seed(123)
train_ind <- sample(seq_len(nrow(Shortoftrainfrog)), size = short_smp_size)

short_trainfrog <- Shortoftrainfrog[train_ind, ]
short_testfrog <- Shortoftrainfrog[-train_ind, ]
#####
pred1svm<-predict(shortfittedsvm,short_testfrog)
plot(pred1svm)

Support Vector Machines with recordId for 4th Dataset

# Support Vector Machines with recordId 

library(e1071)
set.seed(124)
#the original train data had 1799 observations with 26 variables which required a very long run time in r for support vector machine code
#Therefore a short version of train data is used for this svm method for time concerns. This short version contains 218 observations
#from all over the data with 26 variables.

Shortoftrainfrog <- read.csv(file="C:/Users/Gizem/Desktop/hw4gz/Short_Frogs_MFCCs.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")
shortfittedsvm<-svm(RecordID~.,data = Shortoftrainfrog,kernel="radial")
print(shortfittedsvm)
## 
## Call:
## svm(formula = RecordID ~ ., data = Shortoftrainfrog, kernel = "radial")
## 
## 
## Parameters:
##    SVM-Type:  eps-regression 
##  SVM-Kernel:  radial 
##        cost:  1 
##       gamma:  0.025 
##     epsilon:  0.1 
## 
## 
## Number of Support Vectors:  56
####with the same variables;
## 75% of the sample size
short_smp_size <- floor(0.75 * nrow(Shortoftrainfrog))

## set the seed to make your partition reproducible
set.seed(123)
train_ind <- sample(seq_len(nrow(Shortoftrainfrog)), size = short_smp_size)

short_trainfrog <- Shortoftrainfrog[train_ind, ]
short_testfrog <- Shortoftrainfrog[-train_ind, ]
#####
pred1svm<-predict(shortfittedsvm,short_testfrog)
plot(pred1svm)
